#sample test
f1 <- function (n) {
    list <- list()
    for(i in 1:n) {
        list <- append(list, i)
    }
    return(list)
}

f2 <- function (n) {
    list <- list()
    for(i in 1:n) {
        list[[length(list) + 1]] <- i
    }
    return(list)
}
microbenchmark(f1(30000), times = 3)

files <- dir("data/", pattern = "\\.csv$", full.names = TRUE)
df <- vector("character", length(files))
for (file in seq_along(files)) {
  df[[i]] <- read_csv(files[[i]])
}
df <- bind_rows(df)
show_mean <- function(df) {
  for (i in seq_along(df)) {
    if (is.numeric(df[[i]])) {
      cat(str_c(names(df[i]), round(mean(df[[i]]), 2), sep = " - "),
          "\n")
    }
  }
}

show_mean(iris)

  1. The code lists two variables, disp and am. disp is the value multiplied by 0.0163871 and am is a factor variable with the value either auto ot manual.
trans <- list( 
  disp = function(x) x * 0.0163871,
  am = function(x) {
    factor(x, labels = c("auto", "manual"))
  }
)
for (var in names(trans)) {
  mtcars[[var]] <- trans[[var]](mtcars[[var]])
}
col_summary <- function(df, fun) {
  out <- vector("double", length(df))
  for (i in seq_along(df)) {
    out[i] <- fun(df[[i]])
  }
  out
}

  1. You can add text at any point in a plot. You only need to have the proper coordinates for where you want your text to be.
ggplot(data = mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  annotate("text", x = 6, y = 40, label = "yesssss")

  1. The four arguments for arrow within geom_segment are:

angle : angle of arrow head
length : length of the arrow head ends: ends of the line type: whether the arrow head is closed or open

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_segment(aes(x = 7, y = 30, xend = 5.5, yend = 6, colour = "segment"),
               arrow = arrow(angle = 30, length = unit(0.5, "cm"),
                             ends = "first", type = "open")
               )
